<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43319269" data-cid="43319269">
    <div id="comment_43319269">
        <header data-points="4" data-reason="Insightful">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:idiocy"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:idiocy<span> (4, Insightful)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~hedwards" class="author" title="author name and user ID">hedwards (940851) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3598035&cid=43319269">(#43319269)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43319269" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="4" data-reason="Insightful">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>The research for this kind of stuff is pretty weak and inconclusive. What's more, the results regularly go back and forth and are generally done in a post hoc fashion after the data is collected. Now, when they take that data and start making reproducible predictions about who will and won't get sick, then I'll take it seriously. Until then it's just pseudoscience at best.</p><p>Alcohol is a poison, there is no quantity which isn't poisonous, however in sufficiently low concentrations it's not likely to do much harm to the body. Nobody should be recommending that people take up drinking for health benefits as the evidence is shaky at best.</p><p>This isn't the same as when people suggest that it's a bad idea to kill all the bacteria around them, there's a reason to be nice to the bacteria, they often times do helpful things for us, and it's mostly just certain strains that cause problems and cases where the immune system is weak that harsher measures are needed.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_43319269">
