<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43319375" data-cid="43319375">
    <div id="comment_43319375">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="So many differences"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>So many differences<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~EmperorOfCanada" class="author" title="author name and user ID">EmperorOfCanada (1332175) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3598035&cid=43319375">(#43319375)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43319375" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body">The differences between phones, signal strengths, antenna designs, usage patterns, frequencies, etc. are so vast that even if a connection to some disease is found it will probably not apply to the phones in use when the discovery is proven. Then to make it worse any phone technology that might have been harmful would generally cause the worst disease among seriously heavy cellphone users who tend to have the latest and greatest so when investigating a connection you will ask them which technologies they have used and they will probably reply "All of the above" assuming they knew the name of any technology they used.<br> <br>
So the study I would like would involve piles of mice blasted with every technology ever used in general use.</div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_43319375">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="3598035" data-cid="43319375">
